{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"faf7f3dc-6791-41ae-ae85-4c2411e32fe5","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the recommended cross-platform .NET diagnostic tool and works great for CPU profiling.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing:\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Deeper OS-level ETW traces, GC analysis |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live triage (`dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>`) |\n| **dotnet-dump** | If you want a heap/thread snapshot instead |\n\n### Tip for production:\n`dotnet-trace` has low overhead with `cpu-sampling`, so it's safe to run on a live server. If you need kernel-level CPU stacks (e.g., time in native/OS code), use **PerfView** with:\n\n```powershell\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -ThreadTime\n```\n\nStart with `dotnet-trace` — it covers most .NET CPU issues and the output is easy to analyze.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ddbe727f-eb0e-400e-ad01-f15e18c731cc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":393},"id":"988068de-ce5f-431f-9cc5-b3b3a11a3f32","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:50:09.679Z","parentId":"7258a584-6180-4e9c-80db-9bce470486a5"}
